# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: restify-node
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:restify-node/home] Note that by default, curl uses `Connection: keep-alive`.
[src:restify-node/home] In order to make the HEAD method return right away, you’ll need to pass `Connection: close`.
[src:restify-node/home] Since curl is often used with REST APIs, restify’s plugins include a plugin to work around this idiosyncrasy in curl.
[src:restify-node/home] The plugin checks whether the user agent is curl.
[src:restify-node/home] If it is, it sets the Connection header to “close” and removes the “Content-Length” header.
[src:restify-node/home] All three handler chains accept either a single function, multiple functions, or an array of functions.
[src:restify-node/home] The `pre` handler chain is executed before routing.
[src:restify-node/home] That means these handlers will execute for an incoming request even if it’s for a route that you did not register.
[src:restify-node/home] This can be useful for logging metrics or for cleaning up the incoming request before routing it.
[src:restify-node/home] The `use` handler chains is executed after a route has been chosen to service the request.
[src:restify-node/home] Function handlers that are attached via the `use()` method will be run for all routes.
[src:restify-node/home] Since restify runs handlers in the order they are registered, make sure that all your `use()` calls happen before defining any routes.
[src:restify-node/home] Upon completion of each function in the handler chain, you are responsible for calling `next()`.
[src:restify-node/home] Calling `next()` will move to the next function in the chain.
[src:restify-node/home] Unlike other REST frameworks, calling `res.send()` does not trigger `next()` automatically.
[src:restify-node/home] In many applications, work can continue to happen after `res.send()`, so flushing the response is not synonymous with completion of a request.
[src:restify-node/home] In the normal case, `next()` does not typically take any parameters.
[src:restify-node/home] `next()` also accepts any object for which `instanceof Error` is true, which will cause restify to send that Error object as a response to the client.
[src:restify-node/home] The status code for the response will be inferred from the Error object’s `statusCode` property.
[src:restify-node/home] If no `statusCode` is found, it will default to 500.
[src:restify-node/home] The difference between the two is that invoking `next()` with an Error object allows you to leverage the server’s event emitter.
[src:restify-node/home] This enables you to handle all occurrences of an error type using a common handler.
[src:restify-node/home] See the error handling section for more details.
[src:restify-node/home] Lastly, you can call `next.ifError(err)` with an Error object to cause restify to throw, bringing down the process.
[src:restify-node/home] This can be useful if you an Error is surfaced that cannot be handled, requiring you to kill the process.
[src:restify-node/home] restify routing, in ‘basic’ mode, is pretty much identical to express/sinatra, in that HTTP verbs are used with a parameterized resource to determine what chain of handlers to run.
[src:restify-node/home] Values associated with named placeholders are available in `req.params`.
[src:restify-node/home] Those values will be URL-decoded before being passed to you.
[src:restify-node/home] Would result in `req.params[0]` being `foo` and `req.params[1]` being `my/cats/name/is/gandalf`.
[src:restify-node/home] Routes can be specified by any of the following http verbs - `del`, `get`, `head`, `opts`, `post`, `put`, and `patch`.
[src:restify-node/home] If a parameterized route was defined with a string (not a regex), you can render it from other places in the server.
[src:restify-node/home] This is useful to have HTTP responses that link to other resources, without having to hardcode URLs throughout the codebase.
[src:restify-node/home] Both path and query strings parameters get URL encoded appropriately.
[src:restify-node/home] In the first case, we didn’t specify an `Accept-Version` header at all, so restify treats that like sending a `*`.
[src:restify-node/home] Much as not sending an `Accept` header means the client gets the server’s choice.
[src:restify-node/home] Restify will choose this highest matching route.
[src:restify-node/home] In the second case, we explicitly asked for for V1, which got us response a response from the version 1 handler function, but then we asked for V2 and got back JSON.
[src:restify-node/home] Finally, we asked for a version that doesn’t exist and got an error.
[src:restify-node/home] You can default the versions on routes by passing in a version field at server creation time.
[src:restify-node/home] In this case you may need to know more information such as what the original requested version string was, and what the matching version from the routes supported version array was.
[src:restify-node/home] Incoming HTTP requests that contain a `Connection: Upgrade` header are treated somewhat differently by the node HTTP server.
[src:restify-node/home] If you want restify to push Upgrade requests through the regular routing chain, you need to enable `handleUpgrades` when creating the server.
[src:restify-node/home] To determine if a request is eligible for Upgrade, check for the existence of `res.claimUpgrade()`.
[src:restify-node/home] This method will return an object with two properties: the `socket` of the underlying connection, and the first received data `Buffer` as `head` (may be zero-length).
[src:restify-node/home] Once `res.claimUpgrade()` is called, `res` itself is marked unusable for further HTTP responses; any later attempt to `send()` or `end()`, etc, will throw an `Error`.
[src:restify-node/home] Likewise if `res` has already been used to send at least part of a response to the client, `res.claimUpgrade()` will throw an `Error`.
[src:restify-node/home] Upgrades and regular HTTP Response behaviour are mutually exclusive on any particular connection.
[src:restify-node/home] Using the Upgrade mechanism, you can use a library like watershed to negotiate WebSockets connections.
[src:restify-node/home] If a content-type can’t be determined, then restify will respond with an error.
[src:restify-node/home] If a content-type can be negotiated, restify then determines what formatter to use to format the response’s content.
[src:restify-node/home] If no formatter matching the content-type can be found, restify will by default override the response’s content-type to `'application/octet-stream'` and then error if no formatter is found for that content-type.
[src:restify-node/home] This default behavior can be changed by passing `strictFormatters: false` (default is false) when creating the restify server instance.
[src:restify-node/home] In that case, if no formatter is found for the negotiated content-type, the response is flushed without applying any formatter.
[src:restify-node/home] Note in the examples above we’ve not defined any formatters, so we’ve been leveraging the fact that restify ships with `application/json`, `text/plain` and `application/octet-stream` formatters.
[src:restify-node/home] As previously noted, restify ships with built-in formatters for json, text, and binary.
[src:restify-node/home] The restify response object retains has all the “raw” methods of a node ServerResponse on it as well.
[src:restify-node/home] It is common to want to handle an error conditions the same way.
[src:restify-node/home] As an example, you may want to serve a 500 page on all `InternalServerErrors`.
[src:restify-node/home] In this case, you can add a listener for the `InternalServer` error event that is always fired when this Error is encountered by restify as part of a `next(error)` statement.
[src:restify-node/home] This gives you a way to handle all errors of the same class identically across the server.
[src:restify-node/home] You can also use a generic `restifyError` event which will catch errors of all types.
[src:restify-node/home] A module called restify-errors exposes a suite of error constructors for many common http and REST related errors.
[src:restify-node/home] These constructors can be used in conjunction with the `next(err)` pattern to easily leverage the server’s event emitter.
[src:restify-node/home] The full list of constructors can be viewed over at the restify-errors repository.
[src:restify-node/home] This automatic serialization happens because the JSON formatter will call `JSON.stringify()` on the Error object, and all restify-errors have a `toJSON` method defined.
[src:restify-node/home] If you want to use custom errors, make sure you have `toJSON` defined, or use restify-error’s `makeConstructor()` method to automatically create Errors that are supported with with `toJSON`.
[src:restify-node/home] restify-errors provides constructors that inherit from either HttpError or RestError.
[src:restify-node/home] All HttpErrors have a numeric http `statusCode` and `body` properties.
[src:restify-node/home] The statusCode will automatically set the HTTP response status code, and the body attribute by default will be the message.
[src:restify-node/home] All status codes between 400 and 5xx are automatically converted into an HttpError with the name being ‘PascalCase’ and spaces removed.
[src:restify-node/home] For the complete list, take a look at the node source.
[src:restify-node/home] From that code above `418: I'm a teapot` would be `ImATeapotError`, as an example.
[src:restify-node/home] A common problem with REST APIs and HTTP is that they often end up needing to overload 400 and 409 to mean a bunch of different things.
[src:restify-node/home] There’s no real standard on what to do in these cases, but in general you want machines to be able to (safely) parse these things out, and so restify defines a convention of a `RestError`.
[src:restify-node/home] A `RestError` is a subclass of one of the particular `HttpError` types, and additionally sets the body attribute to be a JS object with the attributes `code` and `message`.
[src:restify-node/home] The constructor takes `message`, `statusCode`, `restCode`, and `context` options.
[src:restify-node/home] Please check out the restify-errors repo for more information.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] include the representation data in the body.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following is a request with no body.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:restify-node/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Web browsers have a dedicated JavaScript engine that executes the client code.
[src:restify-node/javascript] These engines are also utilized in some servers and a variety of apps.
[src:restify-node/javascript] The most popular runtime system for non-browser usage is Node.js.
[src:restify-node/javascript] JavaScript is a high-level, often just-in-time–compiled language that conforms to the ECMAScript standard.
[src:restify-node/javascript] It has dynamic typing, prototype-based object-orientation, and first-class functions.
[src:restify-node/javascript] It is multi-paradigm, supporting event-driven, functional, and imperative programming styles.
[src:restify-node/javascript] It has application programming interfaces (APIs) for working with text, dates, regular expressions, standard data structures, and the Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:restify-node/javascript] The ECMAScript standard does not include any input/output (I/O), such as networking, storage, or graphics facilities.
[src:restify-node/javascript] In practice, the web browser or other runtime system provides JavaScript APIs for I/O.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Although Java and JavaScript are similar in name and syntax, the two languages are distinct and differ greatly in design.
[src:restify-node/javascript] The first popular web browser with a graphical user interface, Mosaic, was released in 1993.
[src:restify-node/javascript] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released a more polished browser, Netscape Navigator, in 1994.
[src:restify-node/javascript] During these formative years of the Web, web pages could only be static, lacking the capability for dynamic behavior after the page was loaded in the browser.
[src:restify-node/javascript] There was a desire in the flourishing web development scene to remove this limitation, so in 1995, Netscape decided to add a programming language to Navigator.
[src:restify-node/javascript] They pursued two routes to achieve this: collaborating with Sun Microsystems to embed the Java language, while also hiring Brendan Eich to embed the Scheme language.
[src:restify-node/javascript] The goal was a "language for the masses", "to help nonprogrammers create dynamic, interactive Web sites".
[src:restify-node/javascript] Netscape management soon decided that the best option was for Eich to devise a new language, with syntax similar to Java and less like Scheme or other extant scripting languages.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Although the new language and its interpreter implementation were called LiveScript when first shipped as part of a Navigator beta in September 1995, the name was changed to JavaScript for the official release in December.
[src:restify-node/javascript] The choice of the *JavaScript* name has caused confusion, implying that it is directly related to Java.
[src:restify-node/javascript] At the time, the dot-com boom had begun and Java was a popular new language, so Eich considered the JavaScript name a marketing ploy by Netscape.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:restify-node/javascript] On the JavaScript front, Microsoft created its own interpreter called JScript.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Microsoft first released JScript in 1996, alongside initial support for CSS and extensions to HTML.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Each of these implementations was noticeably different from their counterparts in Netscape Navigator.
[src:restify-node/javascript] These differences made it difficult for developers to make their websites work well in both browsers, leading to widespread use of "best viewed in Netscape" and "best viewed in Internet Explorer" logos for several years.
[src:restify-node/javascript] In November 1996, Netscape submitted JavaScript to Ecma International, as the starting point for a standard specification that all browser vendors could conform to.
[src:restify-node/javascript] This led to the official release of the first ECMAScript language specification in June 1997.
[src:restify-node/javascript] The standards process continued for a few years, with the release of ECMAScript 2 in June 1998 and ECMAScript 3 in December 1999.
[src:restify-node/javascript] However, the effort to fully standardize the language was undermined by Microsoft gaining an increasingly dominant position in the browser market.
[src:restify-node/javascript] By the early 2000s, Internet Explorer's market share reached 95%.
[src:restify-node/javascript] This meant that JScript became the de facto standard for client-side scripting on the Web.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Microsoft initially participated in the standards process and implemented some proposals in its JScript language, but eventually it stopped collaborating on ECMA work.
[src:restify-node/javascript] During the period of Internet Explorer dominance in the early 2000s, client-side scripting was stagnant.
[src:restify-node/javascript] This started to change in 2004, when the successor of Netscape, Mozilla, released the Firefox browser.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Firefox was well received by many, taking significant market share from Internet Explorer.
[src:restify-node/javascript] In 2005, Mozilla joined ECMA International, and work started on the ECMAScript for XML (E4X) standard.
[src:restify-node/javascript] This led to Mozilla working jointly with Macromedia (later acquired by Adobe Systems), who were implementing E4X in their ActionScript 3 language, which was based on an ECMAScript 4 draft.
[src:restify-node/javascript] The goal became standardizing ActionScript 3 as the new ECMAScript 4.
[src:restify-node/javascript] To this end, Adobe Systems released the Tamarin implementation as an open source project.
[src:restify-node/javascript] However, Tamarin and ActionScript 3 were too different from established client-side scripting, and without cooperation from Microsoft, ECMAScript 4 never reached fruition.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Meanwhile, very important developments were occurring in open-source communities not affiliated with ECMA work.
[src:restify-node/javascript] In 2005, Jesse James Garrett released a white paper in which he coined the term Ajax and described a set of technologies, of which JavaScript was the backbone, to create web applications where data can be loaded in the background, avoiding the need for full page reloads.
[src:restify-node/javascript] This sparked a renaissance period of JavaScript, spearheaded by open-source libraries and the communities that formed around them.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Many new libraries were created, including jQuery, Prototype, Dojo Toolkit, and MooTools.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, with the V8 JavaScript engine that was faster than its competition.
[src:restify-node/javascript] The key innovation was just-in-time compilation (JIT), so other browser vendors needed to overhaul their engines for JIT.
[src:restify-node/javascript] In July 2008, these disparate parties came together for a conference in Oslo.
[src:restify-node/javascript] This led to the eventual agreement in early 2009 to combine all relevant work and drive the language forward.
[src:restify-node/javascript] The result was the ECMAScript 5 standard, released in December 2009.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Ambitious work on the language continued for several years, culminating in an extensive collection of additions and refinements being formalized with the publication of ECMAScript 6 in 2015.
[src:restify-node/javascript] The creation of Node.js in 2009 by Ryan Dahl sparked a significant increase in the usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Node combines the V8 engine, an event loop, and I/O APIs, thereby providing a stand-alone JavaScript runtime system.
[src:restify-node/javascript] As of 2018, Node had been used by millions of developers, and npm had the most modules of any package manager in the world.
[src:restify-node/javascript] The ECMAScript draft specification is currently maintained openly on GitHub, and editions are produced via regular annual snapshots.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Potential revisions to the language are vetted through a comprehensive proposal process.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Now, instead of edition numbers, developers check the status of upcoming features individually.
[src:restify-node/javascript] The current JavaScript ecosystem has many libraries and frameworks, established programming practices, and substantial usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Plus, with the rise of single-page applications and other JavaScript-heavy websites, several transpilers have been created to aid the development process.
[src:restify-node/javascript] As of 2025, the overwhelming majority of websites (98.9%) use JavaScript for client side webpage behavior.
[src:restify-node/javascript] "JavaScript" is a trademark of Oracle Corporation in the United States.
[src:restify-node/javascript] The trademark was originally issued to Sun Microsystems on 6 May 1997, and was transferred to Oracle when they acquired Sun in 2009.
[src:restify-node/javascript] A letter was circulated in September 2024, spearheaded by Ryan Dahl, calling on Oracle to free the JavaScript trademark.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Brendan Eich, the original creator of JavaScript, was among the over 14,000 signatories who supported the initiative.
[src:restify-node/javascript] JavaScript is the dominant client-side scripting language of the Web, with 99% of all websites using it for this purpose.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Scripts are embedded in or included from HTML documents and interact with the DOM.
[src:restify-node/javascript] All major web browsers have a built-in JavaScript engine that executes the code on the user's device.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Over 80% of websites use a third-party JavaScript library or web framework as part of their client-side scripting.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Other notable ones include Angular, Bootstrap, Lodash, Modernizr, React, Underscore, and Vue.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Multiple options can be used in conjunction, such as jQuery and Bootstrap.
[src:restify-node/javascript] However, the term "Vanilla JS" was coined for websites not using any libraries or frameworks at all, instead relying entirely on standard JavaScript functionality.
[src:restify-node/javascript] The use of JavaScript has expanded beyond its web browser roots.
[src:restify-node/javascript] JavaScript engines are now embedded in a variety of other software systems, both for server-side website deployments and non-browser applications.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Initial attempts at promoting server-side JavaScript usage were Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's Internet Information Services, but they were small niches.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Server-side usage eventually started to grow in the late 2000s, with the creation of Node.js and other approaches.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Electron, Cordova, React Native, and other application frameworks have been used to create many applications with behavior implemented in JavaScript.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Other non-browser applications include Adobe Acrobat support for scripting PDF documents and GNOME Shell extensions written in JavaScript.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Oracle used to provide Nashorn, a JavaScript interpreter, as part of their Java Development Kit (JDK) API library along with **jjs** a command line interpreter as of JDK version 8.
[src:restify-node/javascript] As a replacement Oracle offered GraalJS which can also be used with the OpenJDK which allows one to create and reference Java objects in JavaScript code and add runtime scripting in JavaScript to applications written in Java.
[src:restify-node/javascript] JavaScript has been used in some embedded systems, usually by leveraging Node.js.
[src:restify-node/javascript] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:restify-node/javascript] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:restify-node/javascript] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:restify-node/javascript] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:restify-node/javascript] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:restify-node/javascript] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:restify-node/javascript] A JavaScript engine must be embedded within a runtime system (such as a web browser or a standalone system) to enable scripts to interact with the broader environment.
[src:restify-node/javascript] The runtime system includes the necessary APIs for input/output operations, such as networking, storage, and graphics, and provides the ability to import scripts.
[src:restify-node/javascript] JavaScript is a single-threaded language.
[src:restify-node/javascript] The runtime processes messages from a queue one at a time, and it calls a function associated with each new message, creating a call stack frame with the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:restify-node/javascript] The call stack shrinks and grows based on the function's needs.
[src:restify-node/javascript] When the call stack is empty upon function completion, JavaScript proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:restify-node/javascript] This is called the event loop, described as "run to completion" because each message is fully processed before the next message is considered.
[src:restify-node/javascript] However, the language's concurrency model describes the event loop as non-blocking: program I/O is performed using events and callback functions.
[src:restify-node/javascript] This means, for example, that JavaScript can process a mouse click while waiting for a database query to return information.
[src:restify-node/javascript] The notable standalone runtimes are Node.js, Deno, and Bun.
[src:restify-node/javascript] The following features are common to all conforming ECMAScript implementations unless explicitly specified otherwise.
[src:restify-node/javascript] The number of cited reserved words including keywords is 50–60 and varies depending on the implementation.
[src:restify-node/javascript] JavaScript supports much of the structured programming syntax from C (e.g., `if` statements, `while` loops, `switch` statements, `do while` loops, etc.).
[src:restify-node/javascript] One partial exception is scoping: originally JavaScript only had function scoping with `var`; block scoping was added in ECMAScript 2015 with the keywords `let` and `const`.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Like C, JavaScript makes a distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:restify-node/javascript] One syntactic difference from C is automatic semicolon insertion, which allow semicolons (which terminate statements) to be omitted.
[src:restify-node/javascript] JavaScript is weakly typed, which means certain types are implicitly cast depending on the operation used.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Values are cast to numbers by casting to strings and then casting the strings to numbers.
[src:restify-node/javascript] These processes can be modified by defining `toString` and `valueOf` functions on the prototype for string and number casting respectively.
[src:restify-node/javascript] JavaScript has received criticism for the way it implements these conversions as the complexity of the rules can be mistaken for inconsistency.
[src:restify-node/javascript] For example, when adding a number to a string, the number will be cast to a string before performing concatenation, but when subtracting a number from a string, the string is cast to a number before performing subtraction.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Often also mentioned is `{} + []` resulting in `0` (number).
[src:restify-node/javascript] This is misleading: the `{}` is interpreted as an empty code block instead of an empty object, and the empty array is cast to a number by the remaining unary `+` operator.
[src:restify-node/javascript] If the expression is wrapped in parentheses - `({} + [])` – the curly brackets are interpreted as an empty object and the result of the expression is `"[object Object]"` as expected.
[src:restify-node/javascript] JavaScript is dynamically typed like most other scripting languages.
[src:restify-node/javascript] A type is associated with a value rather than an expression.
[src:restify-node/javascript] For example, a variable initially bound to a number may be reassigned to a string.
[src:restify-node/javascript] JavaScript supports various ways to test the type of objects, including duck typing.
[src:restify-node/javascript] JavaScript includes an `eval` function that can execute statements provided as strings at run-time.
[src:restify-node/javascript] In JavaScript, an object is an associative array, augmented with a prototype (see below); each key provides the name for an object property, and there are two syntactical ways to specify such a name: dot notation (`obj.x = 10`) and bracket notation (`obj["x"] = 10`).
[src:restify-node/javascript] A property may be added, rebound, or deleted at run-time.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Most properties of an object (and any property that belongs to an object's prototype inheritance chain) can be enumerated using a `for...in` loop.
[src:restify-node/javascript] JavaScript uses prototypes where many other object-oriented languages use classes for inheritance, but it's still possible to simulate most class-based features with the prototype system.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Additionally, ECMAScript version 6 (released June 2015) introduced the keywords **class**, **extends** and **super**, which serve as syntactic sugar to abstract the underlying prototypal inheritance system with a more conventional interface.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Constructors are declared by specifying a method named **constructor**, and all classes are automatically subclasses of the base class Object, similarly to Java.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Though the underlying object mechanism is still based on prototypes, the newer syntax is similar to other object oriented languages.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Private variables are declared by prefixing the field name with a number sign (#), and polymorphism is not directly supported, although it can be emulated by manually calling different functions depending on the number and type of arguments provided.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Functions double as object constructors, along with their typical role.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Prefixing a function call with *new* will create an instance of a prototype, inheriting properties and methods from the constructor (including properties from the `Object` prototype).
[src:restify-node/javascript] ECMAScript 5 offers the `Object.create` method, allowing explicit creation of an instance without automatically inheriting from the `Object` prototype (older environments can assign the prototype to `null`).
[src:restify-node/javascript] The constructor's `prototype` property determines the object used for the new object's internal prototype.
[src:restify-node/javascript] New methods can be added by modifying the prototype of the function used as a constructor.
[src:restify-node/javascript] JavaScript's built-in classes, such as `Array` and `Object`, also have prototypes that can be modified.
[src:restify-node/javascript] However, it's generally considered bad practice to modify built-in objects, because third-party code may use or inherit methods and properties from these objects, and may not expect the prototype to be modified.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Unlike in many object-oriented languages, in JavaScript there is no distinction between a function definition and a method definition.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Rather, the distinction occurs during function calling.
[src:restify-node/javascript] When a function is called as a method of an object, the function's local *this* keyword is bound to that object for that invocation.
[src:restify-node/javascript] JavaScript functions are first-class; a function is considered to be an object.
[src:restify-node/javascript] As such, a function may have properties and methods, such as `.call()` and `.bind()`.
[src:restify-node/javascript] A *nested* function is a function defined within another function.
[src:restify-node/javascript] It is created each time the outer function is invoked.
[src:restify-node/javascript] In addition, each nested function forms a lexical closure: the lexical scope of the outer function (including any constant, local variable, or argument value) becomes part of the internal state of each inner function object, even after execution of the outer function concludes.
[src:restify-node/javascript] JavaScript also supports anonymous functions.
[src:restify-node/javascript] JavaScript supports implicit and explicit delegation.
[src:restify-node/javascript] JavaScript natively supports various function-based implementations of Role patterns like Traits and Mixins.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Such a function defines additional behavior by at least one method bound to the `this` keyword within its `function` body.
[src:restify-node/javascript] A Role then has to be delegated explicitly via `call` or `apply` to objects that need to feature additional behavior that is not shared via the prototype chain.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Whereas explicit function-based delegation does cover composition in JavaScript, implicit delegation already happens every time the prototype chain is walked in order to, e.g., find a method that might be related to but is not directly owned by an object.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Once the method is found it gets called within this object's context.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Thus inheritance in JavaScript is covered by a delegation automatism that is bound to the prototype property of constructor functions.
[src:restify-node/javascript] An indefinite number of parameters can be passed to a function.
[src:restify-node/javascript] The function can access them through formal parameters and also through the local `arguments` object.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Variadic functions can also be created by using the `bind` method.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Like in many scripting languages, arrays and objects (associative arrays in other languages) can each be created with a succinct shortcut syntax.
[src:restify-node/javascript] In fact, these literals form the basis of the JSON data format.
[src:restify-node/javascript] JavaScript supports regular expressions for text searches and manipulation.
[src:restify-node/javascript] A built-in Promise object provides functionality for handling promises and associating handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual result.
[src:restify-node/javascript] JavaScript supplies combinator methods, which allow developers to combine multiple JavaScript promises and do operations based on different scenarios.
[src:restify-node/javascript] The methods introduced are: Promise.race, Promise.all, Promise.allSettled and Promise.any.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Async/await allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written, with minimal overhead, structured similarly to traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Variables in JavaScript can be defined using either the `var`, `let` or `const` keywords.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Variables defined without keywords will be defined at the global scope.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Arrow functions were first introduced in 6th Edition – ECMAScript 2015.
[src:restify-node/javascript] They shorten the syntax for writing functions in JavaScript.
[src:restify-node/javascript] Arrow functions are anonymous, so a variable is needed to refer to them in order to invoke them after their creation, unless surrounded by parenthesis and executed immediately.
